Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Remove the @21 Day Aged British Sirloin Steaks{2} from your fridge to allow them come up to room temperature. Bring a large #saucepan{} of @water{1%litre} with @salt{1/2%tsp} to the boil. Peel and slice the @potatoes{450%g} into 1cm thick rounds. Once boiling, add the potato slices to the water and simmer until just tender, ~{8-12%minutes}.

Meanwhile, trim the @green beans{80%g}. Halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}. Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves} (or use a #garlic press{}). Once the potatoes are cooked, reserve some of the potato cooking water as @Reserved Potato Water{75%ml}, then carefully drain in a #colander{}.

> The potatoes are cooked when you can easily slip a knife through them.

When the potatoes are cooked, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large pan on medium heat. Add the onion and cook until softened, ~{5-6%minutes}, then add the garlic and cook until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}. Then add the @creme fraiche{150%g}, @Vegetable Stock Paste{10%g} and reserved potato water. Mix together, bring to the boil, then remove from the heat. Season to taste with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}. Lay the cooked potato slices in layers in an appropriately sized #ovenproof dish{}, then pour over the creamy sauce. Bake on the top shelf of your oven until golden brown and bubbly, ~{15-20%minutes}.

> Put the dish onto a baking tray to catch any drips.

When 10 mins of dauphinoise cooking time remain, heat a drizzle of oil in a large #frying pan{} on high heat. Season the steaks with @salt and @ground black pepper{}. When hot, lay the steaks into the frying pan and fry until browned, ~{1%minute} on each side. Lower the heat slightly and cook for another ~{1-2%minutes} on each side if you want them medium-rare.

> Cook for 1-2 mins more if you like it more well done.

Once cooked, transfer to a #board{}, cover with #foil{} and allow to rest for a couple of minutes.

> Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat. The steak is safe to eat when the outside is browned.

While the steaks fry, heat a drizzle of oil in another frying pan on medium-high heat. Once hot, add the green beans and stir-fry until starting to char, ~{2-3%minutes}. Stir in the garlic, turn the heat down to medium and cook for ~{1%minute}. Then add a splash of @water{} and immediately cover with a #lid{} or some foil. Allow to cook until the beans are tender, ~{4-5%minutes}. Remove the pan from the heat.

While the beans cook, pour the @Water for the Sauce{150%ml} into the (now empty) #steak pan{}. Bring to the boil, then stir in the @Red Wine Jus Paste{15%g}. Reduce the heat slightly, then bubble away until the sauce has reduced by half, ~{5-6%minutes}. Add in the steak resting juices if you'd like, then bring back to the boil until piping hot. Once glossy and thickened, remove from the heat.

When everything is ready, slice the steaks widthways and transfer to your plates. Spoon the red wine jus over the steaks, then serve with the dauphinoise potatoes and green beans alongside. Enjoy!